Here are my observations from the prelimnary analysis,

  1. There are 1599 rows and 13 columns.
  2. I have removed the column named “X” as it was not of much importance to my analysis after which I am left with 1599 rows and 12 columns.
  3. As per the information given about the dataset, the variable “quality” catches my eye, as it is a categorical variable which will help me in my analysis.

Since “quality” is my main focus here, I will be creating a new variable to further simplify the way the quality of the wine is assessed. I am going to divide the dataset based on the quality rating,as follows

  1. If the quality is rated between 0 to 4 then its “low”
  2. If the quality is rated between 5 to 7 then its “medium”
  3. If the quality is rated above 7 then its “high”

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 observations in the dataset with 13 variables.

The 13 features and their short description is as follows:

Fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

Volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine.

Citric acid: mostly used for adding flavor.

Residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops and measured in gms of sugar per liter.

Chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine.

Free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine.

Total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02.

Density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content.

pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale.

Sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, which acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant.

Alcohol: the percent alcohol present in the wine.

Quality: rating of the wine between 0-10 in the given sample

wine_rating: rating of wine as high,medium,low.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature that intrests me is the quality of the wine.

Reflection

In this analysis, my main struggle was to find the factors that are responsible for the production of different quality of wines especially the ‘high’ and the ‘low’ ones. As the data was very centralized towards the ‘medium’ quality. So maybe in future, I can get a dataset about Red Wines with more complete information so that I can build my models more effectively. I was happy to see that the ‘high’ quality wines have high amounts of alcohol and low amounts of residual sugar and volatile acids. For future analysis, I would love to have a dataset, where a rank is given for that particular wine by a number of different wine tasters. This is because, when we include the human element, we get multiple opinions so by including the human element in my analysis, I would be able to have a better understanding of the quality of wine. Having these factors included inside the dataset would result in a different insight altogether in my analysis.
